<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-06-20T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-06-20T17:00:00-05:00" n="367" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d367">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">724.3415/3852: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Bolivia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Des Portes</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">La
                                            Paz</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-06-20T18:00:00-04:00">June 20, 1934—6
                                    p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 7:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>36. Referring to Department’s telegram No. 6,<note n="18" xml:id="d367fn18">June 20, 11 a.m., <hi rend="italic">supra.</hi></note> message was delivered to the Minister
                                for Foreign Affairs who commented that Bolivia is displeased at
                                American propaganda in South America and Geneva for an arms embargo
                                and also on American unfairness of the Proclamation since Paraguay
                                buys little from the United States and will continue to receive
                                supplies from Italy and Argentina.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Des Portes</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>